         <abstract xml:lang="eng">
            <p>This case is based on extensive interviews and conversations with the CEO of Workplace Partners, the director of the Small Business Development Center (SBDC), and the consultants who worked with Workplace Partners. The inspiration for this case is the fact that many small businesses go out of business due to working capital management issues. Through direct work with the SBDC and Workplace Partners this case provides a real life example of the cash management issues faced by small rapidly growing businesses. The student is asked to prepare a cash budget and then asked to consider the benefits and drawbacks of customer credit policies and associated payment patterns, sales mixes, and financing options to cover projected short falls. Students are given the opportunity to make recommendations based on their cash budget. This case can also be taught more broadly using the issues raised in it as a springboard for a more general discussion of working capital management issues, working capital financing options, and other issues faced by small businesses. This case has a difficulty level appropriate for senior-level undergraduate finance courses or a first course in business finance at the graduate level. The case is designed to be taught in approximately two class hours with approximately three hours of outside preparation to be conducted by the students.</p>
         </abstract>
